1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:17,240
Key Management As we've talked about in the cryptography sections,

2
00:00:17,240 --> 00:00:33,240
Key Management is incredibly important.

3
00:00:33,240 --> 00:00:37,240
Key Management As we've talked about in the cryptography sections,

4
00:00:37,240 --> 00:00:40,240
Key Management is incredibly important.

5
00:00:40,240 --> 00:00:45,240
There's one very good reason for that, and it's actually known as Kirchhoff's principle.

6
00:00:45,240 --> 00:00:50,240
Kirchhoff's principle states that a crypto system should be secure,

7
00:00:50,240 --> 00:00:54,240
even if everything about the system is known except the key.

8
00:00:54,240 --> 00:00:57,240
So an attacker can know the ciphertext.

9
00:00:57,240 --> 00:00:59,240
They can know the algorithm that's being used.

10
00:00:59,240 --> 00:01:01,240
They can know the initialization vector.

11
00:01:01,240 --> 00:01:05,240
They can know all of this, but as long as the key is kept secret,

12
00:01:05,240 --> 00:01:08,240
then you'll have a secure system.

13
00:01:08,240 --> 00:01:12,240
And so key management, how we generate, how we distribute,

14
00:01:12,240 --> 00:01:16,240
how we change or rotate keys, how we distribute those keys,

15
00:01:16,240 --> 00:01:20,240
how we destroy those keys, and then finally, if we need to recover those keys,

16
00:01:20,240 --> 00:01:23,240
it's incredibly important that we do all this very well.

17
00:01:23,240 --> 00:01:25,240
So let's walk through each of these steps.

18
00:01:25,240 --> 00:01:30,240
And let's start with key generation, or creation of keys.

19
00:01:30,240 --> 00:01:35,240
Now when we talk about creating a key, what we're actually doing is we have the key space

20
00:01:35,240 --> 00:01:39,240
that we've talked about, all the possible combinations of a key.

21
00:01:39,240 --> 00:01:46,240
And key generation is about randomly selecting one key out of that entire key space.

22
00:01:46,240 --> 00:01:49,240
And we want to randomly select a key.

23
00:01:49,240 --> 00:01:53,240
It would be a very bad idea if our key generation process simply picked keys one after another

24
00:01:53,240 --> 00:01:54,240
in a linear fashion.

25
00:01:54,240 --> 00:01:57,240
Because what do we always want to avoid in cryptography?

26
00:01:57,240 --> 00:01:58,240
Patterns.

27
00:01:58,240 --> 00:02:05,240
And so we need to be able to, as randomly as possible, select a key from the entire key space.

28
00:02:05,240 --> 00:02:07,240
So that's really what key generation is about.

29
00:02:08,240 --> 00:02:14,240
And this has to be an automated process because human beings we are terrible at true randomness.

30
00:02:14,240 --> 00:02:18,240
And so we need to get our computer systems to try and randomly select a key,

31
00:02:18,240 --> 00:02:20,240
except there's one slight wrinkle there.

32
00:02:20,240 --> 00:02:28,240
And that is our computer systems that we used today are also not capable of actually generating truly random numbers.

33
00:02:28,240 --> 00:02:32,240
But what we can use are what are known as pseudo random number generators.

34
00:02:32,240 --> 00:02:36,240
These are generators that, while not truly random,

35
00:02:36,240 --> 00:02:38,240
they're pretty much close enough.

36
00:02:38,240 --> 00:02:42,240
You know, they won't start to reproduce patterns until maybe billions of years down the road.

37
00:02:42,240 --> 00:02:46,240
So good enough to sort of randomly select a key from the entire space, key space.

38
00:02:46,240 --> 00:02:48,240
So that's key generation.

39
00:02:48,240 --> 00:02:51,240
Next is key distribution.

40
00:02:51,240 --> 00:02:53,240
Especially with symmetric keys.

41
00:02:53,240 --> 00:02:57,240
Once a symmetric key has been generated, you've now got the very big problem of how do you get that key

42
00:02:57,240 --> 00:03:00,240
to the other part of that you're communicating with.

43
00:03:00,240 --> 00:03:03,240
We've already talked about one method out of band.

44
00:03:03,240 --> 00:03:07,240
But that's not very efficient. It's often very difficult to do that.

45
00:03:07,240 --> 00:03:10,240
Another method that you could use is key wrapping.

46
00:03:10,240 --> 00:03:14,240
Key wrapping sounds confusing, but let me explain it in a very simple way.

47
00:03:14,240 --> 00:03:17,240
Let's say that you're planning on communicating with someone all week long

48
00:03:17,240 --> 00:03:19,240
and every hour you want to change keys.

49
00:03:19,240 --> 00:03:24,240
So you're going to need a whole bunch of keys, symmetric keys, to communicate with this person all week long.

50
00:03:24,240 --> 00:03:30,240
So to make this process more efficient, what you decide to do is generate a whole bunch of symmetric keys.

51
00:03:30,240 --> 00:03:32,240
Maybe you generate a hundred of them.

52
00:03:32,240 --> 00:03:36,240
And then what you do is you take those hundred symmetric keys, you put them in a bundle,

53
00:03:36,240 --> 00:03:40,240
and you encrypt all of them with one symmetric key.

54
00:03:40,240 --> 00:03:44,240
So you take a whole bunch of symmetric keys, encrypt them with one symmetric key.

55
00:03:44,240 --> 00:03:47,240
And now you only have to do one key distribution.

56
00:03:47,240 --> 00:03:54,240
You only have to communicate that securely, that one key so that you can then securely send the ciphertext of all the other keys.

57
00:03:54,240 --> 00:03:59,240
That's key wrapping, encrypting a bunch of keys with another symmetric key.

58
00:03:59,240 --> 00:04:04,240
And of course the other major method that you can use that we've talked about is hybrid key distribution,

59
00:04:04,240 --> 00:04:07,240
where you use a combination of asymmetric and symmetric.

60
00:04:07,240 --> 00:04:12,240
You use the asymmetric cryptography to send the symmetric key.

61
00:04:12,240 --> 00:04:16,240
Now let's talk about where you actually store the encryption keys.

62
00:04:16,240 --> 00:04:19,240
There's two major physical devices that we're going to talk about here.

63
00:04:19,240 --> 00:04:23,240
First, TPMs, trusted platform modules.

64
00:04:23,240 --> 00:04:28,240
A TPM is actually a little microchip that is built into the motherboard of a system,

65
00:04:28,240 --> 00:04:33,240
to the hardware of a computer system, like a laptop, a server, a cell phone.

66
00:04:33,240 --> 00:04:41,240
A TPM module is actually a tiny little crypto processor that's used to generate and more importantly, store encryption keys.

67
00:04:41,240 --> 00:04:45,240
And a great way to think about this is you've probably heard of this concept of whole drive encryption,

68
00:04:45,240 --> 00:04:49,240
where you encrypt an entire hard drive, so that if a laptop is stolen for instance,

69
00:04:49,240 --> 00:04:53,240
the attacker won't be able to decrypt the data.

70
00:04:53,240 --> 00:04:57,240
But if you're using whole drive encryption, where are the encryption keys stored?

71
00:04:57,240 --> 00:05:02,240
They obviously can't be on the hard drive because if the attacker had the hard drive with the keys on it,

72
00:05:02,240 --> 00:05:04,240
they'd just be able to unlock it.

73
00:05:04,240 --> 00:05:06,240
And this is where TPM modules come in.

74
00:05:06,240 --> 00:05:09,240
If you ever use a device that supports whole drive encryption,

75
00:05:09,240 --> 00:05:14,240
it has to have one of these TPM modules in it because it's on the TPM trusted platform module

76
00:05:14,240 --> 00:05:17,240
that the encryption keys are actually stored.

77
00:05:17,240 --> 00:05:21,240
And these modules are specifically built to be very difficult to break into,

78
00:05:21,240 --> 00:05:24,240
so that even if someone does steal your laptop,

79
00:05:24,240 --> 00:05:29,240
it's very difficult for them to actually extract the keys from a TPM module.

80
00:05:29,240 --> 00:05:35,240
The next type of device we'll talk about is what's known as an HSM, a hardware security module.

81
00:05:35,240 --> 00:05:38,240
And HSM is also designed to securely store keys,

82
00:05:38,240 --> 00:05:41,240
but not just for an endpoint, like a TPM.

83
00:05:41,240 --> 00:05:46,240
Instead, an HSM module stores the encryption keys for the entire organization.

84
00:05:46,240 --> 00:05:51,240
So an HSM module basically just looks like a server, a very hardened server.

85
00:05:51,240 --> 00:05:59,240
It's plugged to the network and you can communicate with an HSM over the network to request the certain keys or to store certain keys.

86
00:05:59,240 --> 00:06:03,240
So just remember, TPM for storing the key keys on an endpoint,

87
00:06:03,240 --> 00:06:07,240
HSM for storing keys for the entire organization.

88
00:06:07,240 --> 00:06:10,240
Next, let's talk about key rotation.

89
00:06:10,240 --> 00:06:15,240
So key rotation is the concept that's a good idea to change your encryption keys on a periodic basis.

90
00:06:15,240 --> 00:06:20,240
The idea here is that if someone were to compromise or figure out your keys,

91
00:06:20,240 --> 00:06:23,240
if you're changing the keys on a periodic basis,

92
00:06:23,240 --> 00:06:27,240
then they'll only get a small amount of your data and not all of it.

93
00:06:27,240 --> 00:06:29,240
So that's the idea of key rotation.

94
00:06:29,240 --> 00:06:33,240
If you ever get a question asking you how often you should rotate your keys,

95
00:06:33,240 --> 00:06:36,240
what do you think the answer would be?

96
00:06:36,240 --> 00:06:39,240
The perfect answer is as often as necessary,

97
00:06:39,240 --> 00:06:42,240
because it's going to entirely depend on the value of the system,

98
00:06:42,240 --> 00:06:46,240
how critical, how valuable the data is that's being encrypted.

99
00:06:46,240 --> 00:06:50,240
And so for very valuable systems, I'll give you an example.

100
00:06:50,240 --> 00:06:55,240
Some VPN solutions that are passing very important data back and forth across the VPN,

101
00:06:55,240 --> 00:06:58,240
they can be rotating encryption keys every few seconds.

102
00:06:58,240 --> 00:07:00,240
Other keys you might rotate only every year.

103
00:07:00,240 --> 00:07:03,240
So it all depends on the value of the system.

104
00:07:03,240 --> 00:07:06,240
Next, let's talk about key recovery.

105
00:07:06,240 --> 00:07:10,240
So if you've accidentally lost or destroyed your keys, how do you get them back?

106
00:07:10,240 --> 00:07:13,240
There's three major methods that you need to know about.

107
00:07:13,240 --> 00:07:15,240
The first is split knowledge.

108
00:07:15,240 --> 00:07:19,240
And the idea behind split knowledge could be as simple as write the key on a piece of paper,

109
00:07:19,240 --> 00:07:23,240
cut the piece of paper in half, give the two pieces of paper to two different people,

110
00:07:23,240 --> 00:07:26,240
and you've split the knowledge of the key.

111
00:07:26,240 --> 00:07:29,240
There's much more advanced ways of doing this so that if part of the paper is lost,

112
00:07:29,240 --> 00:07:34,240
you can recover it and stuff, but split knowledge is simply the idea that you split the knowledge of the key

113
00:07:34,240 --> 00:07:38,240
up amongst two or more different people.

114
00:07:38,240 --> 00:07:41,240
Next is what's known as dual control.

115
00:07:41,240 --> 00:07:46,240
When I think of dual control, I always think about how do they launch the nuclear missiles out of a submarine.

116
00:07:46,240 --> 00:07:48,240
You always have to have the captain in the first mate.

117
00:07:48,240 --> 00:07:52,240
They each put their keys in some sort of console, turn them both at the same time,

118
00:07:52,240 --> 00:07:54,240
and then whew, the missiles launch.

119
00:07:54,240 --> 00:07:56,240
That's the idea behind dual control.

120
00:07:56,240 --> 00:08:00,240
Two or more people have to work together to recover the keys.

121
00:08:00,240 --> 00:08:02,240
Perfect example of this would be a safe.

122
00:08:02,240 --> 00:08:05,240
Where the safe has both the key and a pinpad.

123
00:08:05,240 --> 00:08:09,240
One person would have the key, the other person would have the pinpad,

124
00:08:09,240 --> 00:08:13,240
code, they'd have to work together, dual control too, unlock the safe.

125
00:08:13,240 --> 00:08:16,240
The final method is key escrow.

126
00:08:16,240 --> 00:08:20,240
This is the idea that you store your encryption keys with a trusted third party,

127
00:08:20,240 --> 00:08:26,240
an organization that's specifically in the business of securely storing encryption keys.

128
00:08:26,240 --> 00:08:32,240
Now one final piece, and that is key destruction or key disposition.

129
00:08:32,240 --> 00:08:35,240
How do you go about destroying your encryption keys?

130
00:08:35,240 --> 00:08:40,240
There are instances where you absolutely have to have destroyed every single copy of the key,

131
00:08:40,240 --> 00:08:44,240
and an example of that is what's known as crypto shredding.

132
00:08:44,240 --> 00:08:48,240
So crypto shredding is the idea that you want to be able to securely destroy your data,

133
00:08:48,240 --> 00:08:54,240
but you're not able to use the best destruction method, which is physical destruction of the media.

134
00:08:54,240 --> 00:08:56,240
So think of storing data in the cloud.

135
00:08:56,240 --> 00:08:59,240
If you have data stored in the cloud, and you say to your cloud provider,

136
00:08:59,240 --> 00:09:02,240
hey, I want you to destroy all of my data.

137
00:09:02,240 --> 00:09:06,240
Are they going to destroy the media, the hard drives the data is stored on?

138
00:09:06,240 --> 00:09:12,240
Of course not, because lots of other customers' data is on those same hard drives.

139
00:09:12,240 --> 00:09:15,240
So this is where you could potentially use crypto shredding.

140
00:09:15,240 --> 00:09:20,240
What you would do is you would make sure that your data was all encrypted in the cloud,

141
00:09:20,240 --> 00:09:27,240
and then you would destroy, and listen carefully here, you would destroy every single copy of the key.

142
00:09:27,240 --> 00:09:33,240
And if you've destroyed every single copy of the key, then the data has been crypto shredding.

143
00:09:33,240 --> 00:09:35,240
Crypto shredding.

144
00:09:35,240 --> 00:09:38,240
No one can recover the data because the keys are gone.

145
00:09:38,240 --> 00:09:41,240
And then you could say to your cloud provider, okay, I've crypto shredding my data,

146
00:09:41,240 --> 00:09:43,240
go ahead and delete the data.

147
00:09:43,240 --> 00:09:46,240
The important part here is you're actually crypto shredding the data.

148
00:09:46,240 --> 00:09:50,240
It's a defensible destruction method that you could potentially use in the cloud.

